reviewText: ------------------------------------------------------------------"Rawhide: The Complete Fifth Season"(Paramount-CBS DVD, 2012)------------------------------------------------------------------The "Rawhide" TV show ran from 1959-65, and is one of the best-known and most durable western shows of the 'Fifties and 'Sixties. It co-starred lanky, stoic newcomer Clint Eastwood as foreman Rowdy Yates, leading a close-knit group of cowboys driving a large herd to market. Eastwood, then a relative unknown, exudes pure charisma -- cool yet intense, he steals every scene he's in, even amid a talented ensemble cast headlined by Eric Fleming, who died in an accident the year after the show was cancelled.This 8-disc, two-volume collection gathers 31 episodes of the show's fifth season, originally broadcast between Fall, 1962-Spring, 1963, all handsomely filmed in black-and-white with a combination of studio and on-location shooting. The transfers are quite nice, with image outlines crisp and sharp and excellent sound quality. It's a well-produced, well-written, well-acted show, nostalgic to begin with and just as compelling to modern audiences as it was when it first aired. Fans of "Gunsmoke," "Bonanza" and "The Big Valley" will find this an equally entertaining show - a western lover's delight! (Joe Sixpack, Slipcue film reviews)
summary: Classic western show from the golden age of television

reviewText: At last a complete season release for Rawhide. Eric Fleming continues to deliver a great performance as tough Trail Boss - Gil Favor. Most certainly as the seasons progress all the characters develop, Rowdy becomes far more argumentative and no longer the kid that worships his boss. But it is in Gil Favor we see the greatest character development. In the first couple of seasons Favor was more the straight forward western hero, but gradually the writers and Fleming himself have evolved Gil into a tough almost anti hero. He is usually right, though not always, this is good, he is not infalliable or invincible.We see how tough the job is for a trailboss and at times his crew really do dislike him, however I find the Gil Favor character believable and far more convincing than Rowdy, the ramrod. However Fleming and Eastwood play off each other well and the tension between the characters add another dimension to this wonderful series. All the drovers have finely developed characters and each episode provides us with super, generally gritty entertainment. Sheb Wooley as Pete Nolan is missed but I rather liked Charles Gray as Clay Forrester, whilst he was never up there with Pete he did provide a sharp contrast to Gil and Rowdy. Some of the great episodes this season are Incident of the Four Horsemen, The Reluctant Bridegroom,Spider Rock, Married Widow ( a sublime performance from Fleming in an episode co scripted by Charles Gray), The Hostages ( surprisingly touching), White Eyes,Pale Rider ( a hauntingly scripted ep by Dean Reisner and featuring a fine performance from Eastwood ), and of course many more. So saddle up and ride 'em cowboy, Rawhide continues to roll on!Footnote, the dvd picture and sound quality from my viewing so far is a vast improvement on Season 4's release. Also great to see some episode previews introduced by Fleming or Eastwood.

reviewText: After immersing in several seasons of this superbly reproduced series, some of the characters are starting to get on my nerves - the trail boss shouting down his drovers, the cook whose blistering belligerence begs for a whoopin, the dimwit cook's aide whose role as the laughingstock wears thin fairly quickly, and finally, by Season Five, no further doubt is left that the producers figured Rawhide was the catapult for Eastwood's career, as he takes greater prominence (the covers are no coincidence).  Still, the plots are varied and over the course of each season, follow a geographic logic, concluding in the trail drive's arrival at Sedalia, Missouri.  At the conclusion of each season, you have a sense of having shared the journey to a limited degree, like immersing yourself in a realistic and detailed account of a military campaign.  Rawhide also generally avoids Wagon Train's oppressively soapy orientation. These shows are as clear as they were in the 60s; there's no hint of the passing years.  Anyone who has a hankerin for soaking up some trail dust without spending an afternoon reading their Louis Lamour should have Rawhide at the ready - all the available seasons.Rawhide: The Complete Fifth Season
summary: Top Quality, Variety of Story Lines, Some Aggravating Characters
